    "narrative": "The Ghost Ride the WHIP lineup is anchored today by **Corbin Carroll**, who earns a massive 71.75 score. Despite a tough matchup against Rogers, his elite speed profile and the significant park factors in his favor make him our primary engine for both R and SB. **James Wood** also earns a strong recommendation (66.50) as he leads off against Keller, benefiting from the prime real estate at the top of the order that maximizes his chances for run production. **Josh Naylor** (62.20) and **Trevor Story** (60.10) provide the necessary stability in the heart of our lineup, with **Naylor** capitalizing on a favorable platoon split against King, while **Story** maintains a solid floor against the mid-tier xERA of Abel.\n\nOur most difficult bench decision was choosing between **Austin Riley** and **Giancarlo Stanton**. While **Stanton** provides high raw power, his matchup against a sharp Detmers lowered his efficiency score to 47.89, falling just short of **Riley**, whose 55.05 projection remains more reliable against Meyer. We have also opted to keep **Vinnie Pasquantino** on the pine today; his 47.09 score is heavily suppressed by a negative platoon dynamic against Valdez, which renders him less efficient than our current starters despite his skill set. \n\nManagers should keep a close eye on the weather and late lineup changes, as our reliance on **Seiya Suzuki** (52.29) and **Jose Caballero** (49.74) is somewhat precarious given their exposure to high-level arms like Nola and Detmers. Specifically, **Suzuki** faces an elite-tier catcher defensive tax, and **Caballero** is facing a pitcher in Detmers who presents a significant challenge to our SB upside. While these players are active, their marginal scores suggest they are the first candidates to move to the bench if we need to prioritize cap management later in the week.",
